1
00:00:37,264 --> 00:00:40,995
<i>[Water rushing]</i>

2
00:00:42,002 --> 00:00:47,406
<i>[Projector whirring]</i>

3
00:00:47,474 --> 00:00:49,772
<i>[Girl narrating]</i>
<i>My dad always told me stories about her-</i>

4
00:00:50,878 --> 00:00:54,439
<i>How she was this great</i>
<i>oceanographer.</i>

5
00:00:55,449 --> 00:00:57,917
<i>Stories about</i>
<i>the baby they had...</i>

6
00:00:57,985 --> 00:01:01,079
<i>and how my mom</i>
<i>just had to name her... Nim.</i>

7
00:01:01,155 --> 00:01:03,350
<i>She invented that name.</i>

8
00:01:03,424 --> 00:01:05,949
<i>At least, that's how my dad</i>
<i>tells the story.</i>

9
00:01:08,028 --> 00:01:12,397
<i>That's all my mother is to me now-</i>
<i>just these stories.</i>

10
00:01:13,701 --> 00:01:17,569
<i>But they're really</i>
<i>some amazing stories.</i>

11
00:01:19,373 --> 00:01:24,834
<i>Like the one he calls</i>
<i>"The Oceanographer and the Great Blue Whale."</i>

12
00:01:27,314 --> 00:01:32,047
<i>Once upon a time, the oceanographer</i>
<i>went out on the wide-open sea...</i>

13
00:01:32,119 --> 00:01:36,647
<i>to find out what was in the stomach</i>
<i>of the great blue whale.</i>

14
00:01:36,724 --> 00:01:39,124
[Groans]

15
00:01:39,193 --> 00:01:41,957
<i>As my mother was staring into</i>
<i>the mouth of the whale...</i>

16
00:01:42,029 --> 00:01:44,998
<i>a mysterious ship</i>
<i>came out of nowhere.</i>

17
00:01:46,734 --> 00:01:49,635
<i>It was called</i>
The Buccaneer Ship.

18
00:01:50,838 --> 00:01:53,932
<i>It got much too close,</i>
<i>and it frightened the whale.</i>

19
00:01:54,008 --> 00:01:58,707
<i>And the oceanographer</i>
<i>was swallowed and taken by the sea.</i>

20
00:02:01,782 --> 00:02:05,980
<i>Dad felt that we should sail the ocean</i>
<i>and look for that blue whale-</i>

21
00:02:06,053 --> 00:02:09,113
<i>that, someday, that whale</i>
<i>would bring her back to us.</i>

22
00:02:10,457 --> 00:02:13,392
<i>I think he just missed her.</i>

23
00:02:13,460 --> 00:02:15,394
<i>We both did.</i>

24
00:02:17,398 --> 00:02:21,732
<i>By my fourth birthday,</i>
<i>we had sailed around the globe... twice-</i>

25
00:02:21,802 --> 00:02:24,930
<i>From the Cape of Good Hope</i>
<i>to the tip of Ratagonia...</i>

26
00:02:25,005 --> 00:02:27,439
<i>from Singapore</i>
<i>to the Cook Islands.</i>

27
00:02:28,942 --> 00:02:32,275
<i>Then one day, we found it-</i>

28
00:02:33,480 --> 00:02:35,539
<i>our home.</i>

29
00:02:41,121 --> 00:02:43,055
<i>This is my island.</i>

30
00:02:45,059 --> 00:02:47,721
<i>Not a bad place to grow up, huh?</i>

31
00:02:47,795 --> 00:02:50,491
<i>See, I don't have to</i>
<i>go to school.</i>

32
00:02:50,564 --> 00:02:52,691
<i>- I'm home-schooled.</i>
- Hey, Selkie!

33
00:02:52,766 --> 00:02:54,324
Watch out! Move it!

34
00:02:54,401 --> 00:02:57,029
<i>Or, technically, island-schooled.</i>

35
00:02:57,104 --> 00:03:00,335
- [Grunts]
- Sorry!

36
00:03:00,407 --> 00:03:04,400
- [Caws]
<i>- Everything I know about the world</i>

37
00:03:04,478 --> 00:03:06,537
Galileo!

38
00:03:06,613 --> 00:03:08,547
<i>Like, do you know</i>
<i>that two objects...</i>

39
00:03:08,615 --> 00:03:12,244
<i>no matter how big they are,</i>
<i>will fall at exactly the same speed?</i>

40
00:03:12,319 --> 00:03:16,085
<i>Galileo proved it.</i>
<i>He's my pelican.</i>

41
00:03:17,925 --> 00:03:20,917
<i>Selkie, my sea lion,</i>
<i>taught me how to swim.</i>

42
00:03:20,994 --> 00:03:24,555
<i>- So I returned the favor by teaching her soccer.</i>
- [Giggles]

43
00:03:24,631 --> 00:03:26,963
<i>She's an excellent midfielder.</i>

44
00:03:28,802 --> 00:03:32,932
<i>Oh, and I'll bet you didn't know that</i>
<i>sea turtles and certain species oflizards...</i>

45
00:03:33,006 --> 00:03:35,201
<i>really get on each other's nerves.</i>

46
00:03:35,275 --> 00:03:38,267
[Squawking]

47
00:03:39,680 --> 00:03:41,807
<i>Anything else</i>
<i>I need to know about the world...</i>

48
00:03:41,882 --> 00:03:45,045
<i>I just open one of the books</i>
<i>my dad brought for me.</i>

49
00:03:45,119 --> 00:03:49,453
<i>- With a little imagination, I can go anywhere.</i>
- [Chanting]

50
00:03:49,523 --> 00:03:53,050
[Chanting continues]

51
00:03:54,862 --> 00:03:57,763
<i>All in all, not a bad life.</i>

52
00:03:57,831 --> 00:04:01,267
<i>For dinner, I throw together</i>
<i>some vegetables from our garden.</i>

53
00:04:01,335 --> 00:04:05,829
<i>And for a little extra flavor,</i>
<i>I toss in some freshly dug-up mealworms.</i>

54
00:04:05,906 --> 00:04:08,397
<i>Mmm. My dad's favorite.</i>

55
00:04:08,475 --> 00:04:11,410
Incredible day, Nim.
A new species, I think.

56
00:04:11,478 --> 00:04:13,844
Well, if it's new, remember
what you're naming it.

57
00:04:13,914 --> 00:04:16,178
"Protozoa Nim."
I haven't forgotten.

58
00:04:16,250 --> 00:04:19,651
<i>[Nim narrating]</i>
<i>See, my dad's a marine biologist.</i>

59
00:04:19,720 --> 00:04:22,814
<i>He's obsessed with nanoplankton,</i>
<i>the tiniest little particles in the ocean.</i>

60
00:04:22,890 --> 00:04:26,792
<i>They're not really my thing,</i>
<i>but to each his own, right?</i>

61
00:04:26,860 --> 00:04:30,921
Did you know there are millions
of picoplankton in a milliliter of water?

62
00:04:30,998 --> 00:04:33,694
Protozoa Nim could be here right now.

63
00:04:34,768 --> 00:04:37,293
- [Squawks]
- What? Wha-

64
00:04:37,371 --> 00:04:40,431
- Hey, Lizard!
- He's not "Lizard." His name is Fred.

65
00:04:40,507 --> 00:04:43,305
- [Hisses]
- [Hisses]

66
00:04:43,377 --> 00:04:47,313
<i>For a guy who loves nature,</i>
<i>you'd think he'd be more into animals.</i>

67
00:04:47,381 --> 00:04:51,681
<i>When they have more than one cell,</i>
<i>Jack sort of loses interest.</i>

68
00:04:51,752 --> 00:04:57,213
<i>Scientists write to him from all over the world</i>
<i>with questions about all sorts of things.</i>

69
00:04:57,291 --> 00:04:59,816
<i>He even writes articles sometimes...</i>

70
00:04:59,893 --> 00:05:02,953
<i>like this great one</i>
<i>for</i> National Geographic.

71
00:05:06,800 --> 00:05:09,894
- What's the reading?
- Thirty-seven knots!

72
00:05:11,872 --> 00:05:14,898
<i>Hey, I'm not saying a scientist's</i>
<i>life is for everyone...</i>

73
00:05:14,975 --> 00:05:17,375
<i>but it is the life for us.</i>

74
00:05:20,447 --> 00:05:24,213
<i>Every few months, the supply ship comes,</i>
<i>bringing us things that we need.</i>

75
00:05:24,284 --> 00:05:27,583
<i>New books and paper,</i>
<i>nails and cloth-</i>

76
00:05:27,654 --> 00:05:30,350
<i>All the things we can't</i>
<i>make for ourselves.</i>

77
00:05:32,926 --> 00:05:35,986
<i>We sail out</i>
<i>into the open water to meet it.</i>

78
00:05:37,731 --> 00:05:40,825
<i>No one, not even</i>
<i>the supply ship's captain...</i>

79
00:05:40,901 --> 00:05:45,235
<i>has ever seen how amazing</i>
<i>our little island really is.</i>

80
00:05:45,305 --> 00:05:49,537
We take care of our island, Nim,
our island's gonna take care of us.

81
00:05:50,811 --> 00:05:53,405
<i>And that's the way</i>
<i>we wanna keep it-</i>

82
00:05:53,480 --> 00:05:57,314
<i>our own perfect, secret world.</i>

83
00:05:57,384 --> 00:05:59,852
[Barks]

84
00:06:00,053 --> 00:06:01,953
<i>- [Jack] Are ya ready?</i>
<i>- [Nim] I'm ready.</i>

85
00:06:05,158 --> 00:06:08,093
Ah, bounty.

86
00:06:08,161 --> 00:06:11,392
Look at this-
Heirloom tomato seeds.

87
00:06:11,465 --> 00:06:14,866
<i>- Do you remember those freckled</i>
<i>ones we were reading about?</i>

88
00:06:14,935 --> 00:06:18,371
The new Alex Rover!
<i>My Arabian Adventure.</i>

89
00:06:18,438 --> 00:06:20,599
What do you think happens
in Arabia?

90
00:06:20,674 --> 00:06:22,608
Wait until after dinner, Nim.

91
00:06:22,676 --> 00:06:25,144
No, I'm just gonna start it.

92
00:06:28,649 --> 00:06:31,914
<i>[Nim reading]</i>
<i>"It's been my curse my entire life.</i>

93
00:06:31,985 --> 00:06:36,479
<i>"I do not go looking for trouble,</i>
<i>but somehow it finds me.</i>

94
00:06:36,557 --> 00:06:38,889
<i>[Man's voice overlaps]</i>
<i>The question wasn't, am I going to die?</i>

95
00:06:38,959 --> 00:06:42,258
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>The question was, how am I going to die?</i>

96
00:06:42,329 --> 00:06:47,232
<i>Will it be by my captors' guns,</i>
<i>or will it be death by thirst?</i>

97
00:06:48,569 --> 00:06:52,437
Must be the hero
of my own life story.

98
00:06:52,506 --> 00:06:55,703
Must be the hero
of my own life story.

99
00:06:55,776 --> 00:06:58,870
<i>Must be the hero</i>
<i>of my own life story.</i>

100
00:06:58,946 --> 00:07:01,779
- Where are you taking me?
- [Speaks foreign language]

101
00:07:01,848 --> 00:07:04,078
[Groans]

102
00:07:04,151 --> 00:07:08,815
A special hole, just for you,
Alex Rover.

103
00:07:09,957 --> 00:07:13,620
<i>Ever heard of the Pit of Spiders?</i>

104
00:07:13,694 --> 00:07:16,128
[Laughs]

105
00:07:16,196 --> 00:07:18,426
"Pit of Spiders," huh?

106
00:07:18,498 --> 00:07:21,023
Well, I guess that answers
the "how will I die" question.

107
00:07:21,101 --> 00:07:23,160
[Giggles]

108
00:07:23,236 --> 00:07:25,602
[Grunts]

109
00:07:27,341 --> 00:07:28,865
- [Grunts]
- [Grunts]

110
00:07:36,350 --> 00:07:37,681
- [Grunts]
- [Laughs]

111
00:07:38,919 --> 00:07:41,319
[Swords clang]

112
00:07:44,224 --> 00:07:45,316
[Yells]

113
00:07:46,426 --> 00:07:48,189
Aah!

114
00:07:52,466 --> 00:07:54,866
- [Growling]
- No, no, no, no! Wait, wait, wait, stop!

115
00:07:54,935 --> 00:07:57,335
- Where're you going?
- [Grunts]

116
00:07:57,404 --> 00:08:01,864
[Sighs]
Oh, death by thirst makes a late comeback.

117
00:08:01,942 --> 00:08:03,534
[Giggles]

118
00:08:09,416 --> 00:08:12,977
How did Alex Rover
get to be Alex Rover?

119
00:08:13,053 --> 00:08:16,511
- Well, let's see.
- Was he born with all that courage?

120
00:08:16,590 --> 00:08:18,581
"Was he born with all that courage?"

121
00:08:18,659 --> 00:08:20,627
Hmm.

122
00:08:20,694 --> 00:08:24,425
The thing about courage is...

123
00:08:24,498 --> 00:08:28,832
it's somethin' that we have to learn
and relearn our whole lives.

124
00:08:28,902 --> 00:08:31,370
You know, it's not just in you.

125
00:08:31,438 --> 00:08:34,839
It's in every choice we make,
each and every day.

126
00:08:38,645 --> 00:08:42,843
- Where do you think Alex Rover is
at this very minute?

127
00:08:42,916 --> 00:08:48,877
Maybe he's chained up in a sarcophagus
20,000 fathoms under the sea.

128
00:08:50,190 --> 00:08:52,385
Or in some pit of spiders...

129
00:08:52,459 --> 00:08:55,724
trapped without the antidote
for their poison.

130
00:08:55,796 --> 00:08:58,458
Yeah, pit of spiders.
I like that.

131
00:08:58,532 --> 00:09:01,558
[Sighs]
Okay. Time to get some rest.

132
00:09:04,204 --> 00:09:06,195
Sleep tight, now, okay?

133
00:09:07,808 --> 00:09:10,368
And no dreaming about spiders.

134
00:09:39,573 --> 00:09:42,940
[Screams, shrieks]

135
00:09:43,009 --> 00:09:45,068
Spider! Spider!

136
00:09:47,247 --> 00:09:50,011
[Gasps]
Get away from me.

137
00:09:51,918 --> 00:09:56,855
All right.
These all go back here.

138
00:09:56,923 --> 00:09:59,858
Straight. Right angles.

139
00:10:05,065 --> 00:10:07,363
[Groans, whines]

140
00:10:09,202 --> 00:10:11,966
Is-ls this the, uh,
Telegraph Hill Pharmacy?

141
00:10:12,038 --> 00:10:14,097
Yes, I need a delivery, please.

142
00:10:14,174 --> 00:10:16,108
Uh, Purell.

143
00:10:16,176 --> 00:10:18,701
- Well, h-how many bottles do you have?
- [Voice, indistinct]

144
00:10:18,779 --> 00:10:20,838
Oh. Uh, very good.
All of them.

145
00:10:20,914 --> 00:10:22,848
Yeah. Send 'em all.

146
00:10:28,255 --> 00:10:30,189
- [Rings]
<i>- [Woman] Uh, who is it?</i>

147
00:10:30,257 --> 00:10:33,192
- Telegraph Hill Pharmacy.
<i>- Uh, just leave it there, please.</i>

148
00:10:33,260 --> 00:10:35,228
Just leave it here?
In the rain?

149
00:10:35,295 --> 00:10:38,822
<i>Yeah, go ahead. I-I put it</i>
<i>on my MasterCard. I left you a very nice tip.</i>

150
00:10:38,899 --> 00:10:41,333
<i>- Uh, make sure you get it.</i>
- Okay.

151
00:10:43,370 --> 00:10:45,304
[Sighs]

152
00:10:51,511 --> 00:10:56,175
<i>[Phone rings]</i>

153
00:10:56,249 --> 00:11:00,743
<i>- [Answering machine beeps]</i>
<i>- Alexandra, it's Buffy, your favorite editor.</i>

154
00:11:00,821 --> 00:11:04,086
<i>I know you're there,</i>
<i>and I know you're not going to pick up.</i>

155
00:11:04,157 --> 00:11:06,091
<i>I just worry about you, darling...</i>

156
00:11:06,159 --> 00:11:08,889
<i>sitting at your computer,</i>
<i>living on a diet of only Progresso soup.</i>

157
00:11:10,030 --> 00:11:12,396
<i>- How can you eat that every day?</i>
- Buffy.

158
00:11:12,465 --> 00:11:14,558
<i>So, how is</i>
<i>the new Alex Rover coming?</i>

159
00:11:14,634 --> 00:11:17,467
<i>Wasn't I supposed to read</i>
<i>something two weeks ago?</i>

160
00:11:17,537 --> 00:11:20,131
<i>No pressure, no pressure,</i>
<i>no pressure.</i>

161
00:11:20,207 --> 00:11:23,608
[Bubbling]

162
00:11:29,316 --> 00:11:33,116
<i>See, what you don't know about me</i>
<i>is that where there's an Alex Rover-</i>

163
00:11:33,186 --> 00:11:35,086
[Laughs]
there's a way!

164
00:11:35,155 --> 00:11:39,091
I have a certain knack for getting out of
predicaments far worse than this one, you know.

165
00:11:39,159 --> 00:11:42,890
Eh. Excuse me?
[Chuckles]

166
00:11:42,963 --> 00:11:45,864
No, hold on. No. I'm supposed
to get outta this, you know.

167
00:11:45,932 --> 00:11:50,960
Alexandra!

168
00:11:52,439 --> 00:11:55,897
[Groans]
Why can't I get this? [Sighs]

169
00:11:55,976 --> 00:11:59,571
No pressure, no pressure,
no pressure.

170
00:12:01,214 --> 00:12:03,910
Volcanic sacrifice.
What was I thinking?

171
00:12:03,984 --> 00:12:06,475
<i>Volcano, volcano.</i>

172
00:12:07,554 --> 00:12:11,490
<i>"Living in the Shadow</i>
<i>of a Volcano. "Hmm.</i>

173
00:12:11,558 --> 00:12:14,425
Well, that's just crazy.
I mean, why would anyone do that?

174
00:12:21,134 --> 00:12:23,932
<i>[Waves lapping]</i>

175
00:12:26,740 --> 00:12:29,641
[Panting]

176
00:12:30,644 --> 00:12:33,636
Oh, wow.

177
00:12:33,713 --> 00:12:35,977
Perfect.

178
00:12:55,168 --> 00:12:57,932
- What you doin', Jack?
<i>- Ah, there you are!</i>

179
00:12:58,004 --> 00:13:02,338
Current's shifted, Nim. Zander's Atoll
is gonna be just five feet underwater.

180
00:13:02,409 --> 00:13:04,843
<i>Zander's Atoll?</i>
<i>But it's almost dinner!</i>

181
00:13:04,911 --> 00:13:07,846
<i>Hey, we might not see algae</i>
<i>growth like this for years.</i>

182
00:13:07,914 --> 00:13:09,779
More plankton?

183
00:13:09,849 --> 00:13:11,942
This is the trip
we find Protozoa Nim.

184
00:13:12,018 --> 00:13:14,213
I swear it.
I can feel it in my bones.

185
00:13:14,287 --> 00:13:17,120
But Chicca's eggs are about to hatch.
I need to be here.

186
00:13:17,190 --> 00:13:21,251
No negotiating. I mean,
this is a once-in-a-lifetime experience.

187
00:13:21,328 --> 00:13:25,162
- Come on!
- Yeah, you said that last week

188
00:13:25,231 --> 00:13:29,691
- Two nights, Nim.
- No! Chicca only saved one last year, Jack.

189
00:13:29,769 --> 00:13:32,636
One little turtle. I want to stay.

190
00:13:32,706 --> 00:13:34,970
We can talk
on the satellite phone.

191
00:13:35,041 --> 00:13:37,805
Nim, please.

192
00:13:37,877 --> 00:13:40,345
I'm not a little girl anymore.

193
00:13:42,148 --> 00:13:44,412
[Groans]

194
00:13:44,484 --> 00:13:47,044
You got so much of your mom in you,
you know that?

195
00:13:47,120 --> 00:13:49,554
- That's a good thing, right?
<i>- Yeah, good.</i>

196
00:13:49,622 --> 00:13:51,556
Sure.

197
00:13:51,624 --> 00:13:54,559
Unfortunately, I could never win a fight
with her either.

198
00:13:56,429 --> 00:13:59,193
<i>Okay, it's only four hours</i>
<i>till low tide.</i>

199
00:13:59,265 --> 00:14:02,860
Oh! Hey, could you grab
my collection jars and my wet suit?

200
00:14:02,936 --> 00:14:04,870
<i>I already packed them for you!</i>

201
00:14:04,938 --> 00:14:08,430
Any e-mails show up, tell 'em I'm on expedition.
I'll get to their questions on Thursday.

202
00:14:08,508 --> 00:14:10,442
Hey, Lizard, get off of that.

203
00:14:10,510 --> 00:14:12,239
<i>He's not "Lizard."</i>
<i>His name is Fred.</i>

204
00:14:12,312 --> 00:14:15,281
<i>Unless it's, like,</i>
<i>a ridiculously obvious e-mail.</i>

205
00:14:15,348 --> 00:14:18,681
- Then I can help 'em, right?
- I'd rather you just said Thursday.

206
00:14:18,752 --> 00:14:20,845
Nim, are you sure
you're okay with this?

207
00:14:20,920 --> 00:14:22,717
Come on.
You've left me alone before.

208
00:14:22,789 --> 00:14:24,916
Well, yeah. One night.
But never for two.

209
00:14:24,991 --> 00:14:29,394
Well, look, I've got Selkie and Fred
and Galileo and the new Alex Rover book.

210
00:14:29,462 --> 00:14:32,522
- I'll be excellent.
- All right, all right.

211
00:14:34,567 --> 00:14:37,968
- You just come back with Protozoa Nim!
- I will!

212
00:14:38,038 --> 00:14:41,132
I'll see ya Thursday!
Love you!

213
00:14:41,207 --> 00:14:43,471
Love you too!

214
00:14:43,543 --> 00:14:46,137
I'll radio you tonight!

215
00:14:46,212 --> 00:14:49,613
No parties while I'm gone!

216
00:14:51,451 --> 00:14:55,478
<i>#Baby, baby</i>
<i>please let me hold him #

217
00:14:55,555 --> 00:15:00,049
<i>- #I wanna make him stay up all night #
- [Barks]

218
00:15:00,126 --> 00:15:04,153
<i>#Sister, Sister</i>
<i>He's just a plaything #

219
00:15:04,230 --> 00:15:07,893
<i># We wanna make him</i>
<i>stay up all night #

220
00:15:07,967 --> 00:15:10,265
<i>- #Here we go #
- [Grunting]

221
00:15:13,406 --> 00:15:15,340
[Giggles]

222
00:15:17,877 --> 00:15:22,211
<i>#See him drink from a bottle #

223
00:15:22,282 --> 00:15:23,909
<i>#See him eat from a plate ##</i>

224
00:15:24,150 --> 00:15:25,447
[Computer chimes]

225
00:15:25,518 --> 00:15:28,612
<i>Ooh, two new e-mails.</i>
<i>Aren't we popular?</i>

226
00:15:28,688 --> 00:15:30,417
- [Squawks]
<i>- Hey, Freddie.</i>

227
00:15:30,490 --> 00:15:32,515
How's it goin'?

228
00:15:32,592 --> 00:15:36,892
"Dear Jack Rusoe, I need a bit of help
on my newest adventure.

229
00:15:36,963 --> 00:15:40,956
Might you be able to answer
a few questions for me? Alex Rover."

230
00:15:41,034 --> 00:15:42,934
Alex Rover?

231
00:15:43,002 --> 00:15:45,493
Alex Rover is writing to my dad?

232
00:15:45,572 --> 00:15:48,598
Do you think it's <i>the</i> Alex Rover?

233
00:15:51,544 --> 00:15:56,311
- It's him! It's him! It's really him!
- [Barking]

234
00:15:56,382 --> 00:16:01,843
Dear Alex Rover, I'm sure Jack would love
to help you with your newest adventure.

235
00:16:01,921 --> 00:16:06,290
He's a great fan of yours.
We both are.

236
00:16:06,359 --> 00:16:10,090
- From... Nim.
- [Keyboard clicking]

237
00:16:19,105 --> 00:16:21,039
<i>[Alexandra]</i>
<i>"Dear Alex Rover...</i>

238
00:16:21,107 --> 00:16:24,634
<i>"I'm sure Jack would love to help you</i>
<i>with your newest adventure.</i>

239
00:16:24,711 --> 00:16:29,444
<i>"He'll be back on Thursday.</i>
<i>He's a great fan of yours. We both are.</i>

240
00:16:29,516 --> 00:16:31,711
From Nim."

241
00:16:31,784 --> 00:16:36,050
Nim. Hmm, what an unusual name.

242
00:16:38,358 --> 00:16:42,795
<i>Dear Nim, are you Jack's</i>
<i>research associate?</i>

243
00:16:42,862 --> 00:16:45,524
<i>Jack wrote of a volcano</i>
<i>where you live.</i>

244
00:16:45,598 --> 00:16:49,591
Are you familiar with it?
Sincerely, Alex Rover.

245
00:16:49,669 --> 00:16:51,603
Send.

246
00:16:52,839 --> 00:16:56,866
- What are you doing, Alexandra?
- Um, research.

247
00:16:56,943 --> 00:16:59,104
Go. Go. Go away.
Leave me alone.

248
00:16:59,179 --> 00:17:02,615
You don't mean that.
You love me.

249
00:17:02,682 --> 00:17:05,515
[Snorts]
And what makes you so sure of that, huh?

250
00:17:06,653 --> 00:17:11,056
Because the whole world
loves Alex Rover.

251
00:17:11,124 --> 00:17:14,582
Really? I know.
"Translated into 21 different languages."

252
00:17:14,661 --> 00:17:17,289
No pressure, no pressure,
no pressure.

253
00:17:20,099 --> 00:17:22,033
[Sighs]

254
00:17:22,101 --> 00:17:24,092
You've been writing chapter eight
for three months now.

255
00:17:24,170 --> 00:17:29,437
So either sacrifice me to the damn volcano
or let me find my escape already.

256
00:17:29,509 --> 00:17:33,468
- Hey! It's time to finish the book.
- Shh!

257
00:17:33,546 --> 00:17:36,845
- I'm thinking.
- Yeah. You're thinking. You're thinking.

258
00:17:36,916 --> 00:17:41,410
That's the problem. You've gotta
get outta your head and into your body.

259
00:17:41,487 --> 00:17:44,888
Hey, that's it. Kinka.

260
00:17:44,958 --> 00:17:46,892
"Kinka"?

261
00:17:46,960 --> 00:17:48,894
Kinka!

262
00:17:50,063 --> 00:17:51,997
Kinka!

263
00:17:53,066 --> 00:17:55,967
Kinka!

264
00:17:57,537 --> 00:18:00,802
## [Humming]

265
00:18:02,909 --> 00:18:04,809
[Panting]
Yeah!

266
00:18:11,217 --> 00:18:13,742
[Panting]

267
00:18:13,820 --> 00:18:15,913
<i>[Nim on the phone]</i>
<i>It was incredible, Jack.</i>

268
00:18:15,989 --> 00:18:19,322
<i>Chicca's babies were born</i>
<i>tonight, just like I said.</i>

269
00:18:19,392 --> 00:18:22,520
<i>- [Jack] That's excellent.</i>
<i>- [Nim] And the mole crabs were crazy hungry.</i>

270
00:18:22,595 --> 00:18:27,464
<i>It was so important that I stayed.</i>
<i>I saved all six turtles.</i>

271
00:18:27,533 --> 00:18:29,933
<i>[Jack] Well, they're lucky you were there.</i>
<i>I'm proud of you, honey.</i>

272
00:18:30,003 --> 00:18:33,700
- How's Zander's Atoll?
- Oh, I wish you could see this, Nim. It's-

273
00:18:33,773 --> 00:18:37,174
I mean, it's more incredible
than the Milky Way.

274
00:18:37,243 --> 00:18:39,302
Next time
there's no negotiating, okay?

275
00:18:39,379 --> 00:18:42,143
Have you found
my nanoplankton yet?

276
00:18:42,215 --> 00:18:45,742
Mmm. I have a pretty good
feeling about it.

277
00:18:48,221 --> 00:18:51,452
Now, go to sleep, Nim. No more reading.
We'll talk in the morning.

278
00:18:51,524 --> 00:18:53,719
How did you know I was reading?

279
00:18:53,793 --> 00:18:56,489
[Chuckles]
Oh, I know you pretty well.

280
00:18:58,264 --> 00:19:01,995
Good night, Nim.
Sleep tight.

281
00:19:04,737 --> 00:19:09,071
[Sighs]
It's just magnificent.

282
00:19:12,478 --> 00:19:14,673
<i>[Wind blowing]</i>

283
00:19:23,623 --> 00:19:27,525
<i>[Rain dripping]</i>

284
00:19:29,195 --> 00:19:32,255
<i>[Thunder crashes]</i>

285
00:19:56,723 --> 00:19:58,486
[Grunts]

286
00:20:01,894 --> 00:20:04,226
No!

287
00:20:08,768 --> 00:20:12,761
[Panting]

288
00:20:13,806 --> 00:20:17,071
[Yells]

289
00:20:37,597 --> 00:20:41,260
<i>- [Wind blows]</i>
- [Clinking]

290
00:20:49,542 --> 00:20:53,308
Jack?
Daddy?

291
00:20:53,379 --> 00:20:57,475
<i>[Wind blows]</i>

292
00:20:57,550 --> 00:20:59,541
[Creaking]

293
00:21:11,264 --> 00:21:13,198
<i>Oh, no.</i>

294
00:21:19,639 --> 00:21:22,039
[Grunting]

295
00:21:28,915 --> 00:21:30,405
[Squawks]

296
00:21:30,483 --> 00:21:34,044
- Freddie!
- [Squawking]

297
00:21:37,990 --> 00:21:40,584
<i>[Wind whistling]</i>

298
00:21:43,129 --> 00:21:45,063
[Selkie grunts]

299
00:22:02,615 --> 00:22:04,810
[Sighs]

300
00:22:05,818 --> 00:22:07,786
It's a mess in here, eh, Selk?

301
00:22:19,465 --> 00:22:23,663
No power. This rots.

302
00:22:38,618 --> 00:22:41,416
[Buzzes, whirs]

303
00:22:47,426 --> 00:22:50,190
- [Beeps]
- Jack?

304
00:22:51,364 --> 00:22:56,529
<i>Can you hear me?</i>
<i>Jack... Michael... Rusoe?</i>

305
00:22:57,537 --> 00:23:01,098
<i>Daddy, can you hear me?</i>

306
00:23:01,173 --> 00:23:03,869
<i>- Jack?</i>
- [Caws]

307
00:23:03,943 --> 00:23:06,571
<i>Come in, Daddy!</i>

308
00:23:09,582 --> 00:23:13,211
<i>[Echoing]</i>
<i>Jack? Daddy?</i>

309
00:23:42,815 --> 00:23:46,012
<i>[Galileo cawing]</i>

310
00:23:48,487 --> 00:23:51,820
- [Caws]
- [Groans]

311
00:23:54,927 --> 00:23:58,795
<i>- [Caws]</i>
- [Sputters]

312
00:24:02,401 --> 00:24:04,528
<i>Protozoa Nim.</i>

313
00:24:05,705 --> 00:24:08,902
Leak. Leak is not good.

314
00:24:08,975 --> 00:24:11,466
Nobody likes a leak.

315
00:24:14,947 --> 00:24:17,381
[Caws]

316
00:24:20,219 --> 00:24:23,052
<i>- [Caws]</i>
- Oh. [Sighs]

317
00:24:24,056 --> 00:24:25,990
Middle of nowhere.

318
00:24:27,994 --> 00:24:31,794
No mast. No satellite.

319
00:24:31,864 --> 00:24:34,594
Sinking ship.

320
00:24:37,703 --> 00:24:41,833
How do I get back to Nim?
[Sighs]

321
00:24:55,588 --> 00:24:58,318
- He's not even due back till tomorrow, right, Fred?
- [Squawks]

322
00:24:58,391 --> 00:25:00,689
Nothin' to worry about.

323
00:25:13,606 --> 00:25:16,666
[Clattering]

324
00:25:30,056 --> 00:25:33,219
[Thinking]
Gotta get food. I gotta get strength.

325
00:25:33,292 --> 00:25:35,522
I gotta get back to Nim.

326
00:25:43,135 --> 00:25:45,603
[Yells]
That's my fish! I saw it first!

327
00:25:47,773 --> 00:25:50,105
[Caws]

328
00:25:50,176 --> 00:25:53,737
What? Huh?
Who are you?

329
00:25:55,548 --> 00:25:59,814
<i>Do I know you?</i>
<i>You're one of Nim's friends?</i>

330
00:25:59,885 --> 00:26:01,944
[Caws]

331
00:26:02,021 --> 00:26:06,117
[Chuckles]
I must be gettin' sunstroke. Talkin' to a bird.

332
00:26:06,192 --> 00:26:07,784
<i>[Cawing rapidly]</i>

333
00:26:10,062 --> 00:26:11,154
[Gasps]

334
00:26:18,804 --> 00:26:20,738
[Caws]

335
00:26:32,051 --> 00:26:34,849
<i>[Nim's voice]</i>
<i>You just come back with Protozoa Nim!</i>

336
00:26:34,920 --> 00:26:37,616
I will! I'll see ya Thursday!

337
00:26:37,690 --> 00:26:41,091
- I love you!
<i>- Love you too!</i>

338
00:26:41,160 --> 00:26:43,958
<i>[Jack's Voice]</i>
<i>I'll radio you tonight!</i>

339
00:26:50,970 --> 00:26:54,633
- It's a mess in here, eh, Selk?
- [Grunting]

340
00:27:09,722 --> 00:27:12,486
[Chiming]

341
00:27:12,558 --> 00:27:15,322
Alex Rover?
He's writing to us again?

342
00:27:16,829 --> 00:27:19,627
<i>[Alex]</i>
<i>"Dear Nim, are you Jack's research associate?</i>

343
00:27:19,698 --> 00:27:23,134
<i>"Perhaps you can help me.</i>
<i>I'm up against a very serious deadline.</i>

344
00:27:23,202 --> 00:27:27,366
<i>"Jack wrote of a volcano where you live.</i>
<i>Are you familiar with it?</i>

345
00:27:27,439 --> 00:27:29,999
<i>Sincerely,</i>
<i>Alex Rover. "

346
00:27:31,744 --> 00:27:35,111
Dear Alex Rover,
we do have a volcano-

347
00:27:35,181 --> 00:27:37,115
"Only we call it
Fire Mountain.

348
00:27:37,183 --> 00:27:41,483
It hasn't exploded in years, but when it did,
the sky went completely white with ash."

349
00:27:41,554 --> 00:27:45,820
That's excellent.
"Sky white with ash." I like that image.

350
00:27:45,891 --> 00:27:51,796
All right. Dear Nim, can one really
see bubbling lava...

351
00:27:51,864 --> 00:27:55,163
inside the mouth of a volcano?

352
00:27:56,335 --> 00:27:59,327
Send.
All right.

353
00:27:59,405 --> 00:28:02,067
I can't wait for that.

354
00:28:03,075 --> 00:28:06,738
Oh, no. Mailman.
Oh, no. Hey!

355
00:28:06,812 --> 00:28:10,213
Uh- Uh- Excuse me!
Can you just leave it on the porch?

356
00:28:10,282 --> 00:28:12,876
Can you just leave it
under the door?

357
00:28:12,952 --> 00:28:14,886
<i>- [Shattering]</i>
<i>- Ouch.</i>

358
00:28:16,789 --> 00:28:18,757
<i>[Nim's voice]</i>
<i>Dear Alex Rover...</i>

359
00:28:18,824 --> 00:28:22,726
<i>I'm not sure what it looks like inside</i>
<i>a volcano, but I'll let you know soon.</i>

360
00:28:22,795 --> 00:28:26,060
<i>Sincerely, Nim,</i>
<i>Jack's research associate.</i>

361
00:28:29,268 --> 00:28:31,065
<i>Oh, so much mail.</i>

362
00:28:46,285 --> 00:28:48,913
[Thinking]
I just open the door. Open the door, no big deal.

363
00:28:48,988 --> 00:28:50,922
Just get the mail,
get the mail.

364
00:28:54,727 --> 00:28:57,287
<i>Okay, Fred. No big deal.</i>
<i>Let's do this.</i>

365
00:28:58,998 --> 00:29:01,558
I can do it.
I can do it.

366
00:29:01,634 --> 00:29:04,797
Everyone turns knobs.
You can do it. Come on.

367
00:29:04,870 --> 00:29:10,604
Come on. Just a little farther.
[Grunts]

368
00:29:16,849 --> 00:29:18,783
[Gasps]

369
00:29:20,185 --> 00:29:23,177
Okay, grab it.
One, two, three.

370
00:29:24,390 --> 00:29:25,948
<i>[Horn honks]</i>

371
00:29:26,025 --> 00:29:27,925
- Oh.
<i>- [Helicopter whirring]</i>

372
00:29:33,966 --> 00:29:36,867
[Groans]
Who needs mail?

373
00:29:36,936 --> 00:29:38,870
I can get it tomorrow.

374
00:29:46,512 --> 00:29:48,639
Hmm, interesting.

375
00:29:48,714 --> 00:29:52,275
Not really lava as much as
dry, craggy rock.

376
00:29:52,351 --> 00:29:56,378
- I can't wait to tell Alex Rover.
<i>- [Galileo cawing]</i>

377
00:29:56,455 --> 00:30:00,551
Galileo, we were worried about you!
Where'd you go?

378
00:30:00,626 --> 00:30:03,857
[Cawing]

379
00:30:03,929 --> 00:30:07,387
- We're just doing some research for Alex Rove-
- [Cracking]

380
00:30:07,466 --> 00:30:11,368
- What's that? Hold on, Fred!
- [Squawks]

381
00:30:13,539 --> 00:30:15,666
[Grunting]

382
00:30:18,877 --> 00:30:20,310
<i>[Rocks tumbling]</i>

383
00:30:32,057 --> 00:30:34,821
- [Creaking, snapping]
- [Gasps]

384
00:30:36,495 --> 00:30:38,554
Oh, come on.
Come on, open up!

385
00:30:40,599 --> 00:30:43,227
Open! Unclip, unclip!

386
00:30:43,302 --> 00:30:45,770
[Gasps]

387
00:30:45,838 --> 00:30:48,466
- Come on!
- [Squeaking]

388
00:30:55,247 --> 00:30:59,047
- [Panting]
- [Squawks]

389
00:30:59,118 --> 00:31:01,450
[Gasps]

390
00:31:01,520 --> 00:31:03,784
Aah!

391
00:31:09,661 --> 00:31:12,129
- [Squawks]
- Fred, are you okay?

392
00:31:12,197 --> 00:31:17,999
- [Squawks]
- Let's, um- Let's not tell Jack

393
00:31:18,070 --> 00:31:21,631
<i>"Dear Alex Rover, my volcano expedition</i>
<i>didn't go well at all.</i>

394
00:31:21,707 --> 00:31:26,337
I fell down the face of the mountain
and got a nasty five-inch cut on my leg."

395
00:31:26,412 --> 00:31:28,437
Oh, my. All because of me.

396
00:31:28,514 --> 00:31:31,483
<i>"It's very swollen</i>
<i>and now pus is coming out.</i>

397
00:31:31,550 --> 00:31:36,112
<i>P.S. How would you handle</i>
<i>a five-inch gash with pus coming out?"</i>

398
00:31:38,223 --> 00:31:40,350
What would I do?

399
00:31:44,863 --> 00:31:47,764
<i>[Alexandra's voice] Dear Nim,</i>
<i>the most important thing for a cut...</i>

400
00:31:47,833 --> 00:31:50,267
<i>is to make sure</i>
<i>that it's kept clean and dry.</i>

401
00:31:50,335 --> 00:31:54,635
<i>[Alex's voice] In the Cook Islands,</i>
<i>they use the stem of a Simarouba plant...</i>

402
00:31:54,706 --> 00:31:57,675
<i>- to keep out infection.</i>
- Hmm. Simarouba.

403
00:31:59,044 --> 00:32:01,808
P.S.
Are you all right, Nim?

404
00:32:03,549 --> 00:32:07,815
<i>[Alexandra] "Dear Alex,</i>
<i>regarding your question 'Am I all right? '

405
00:32:07,886 --> 00:32:11,049
"I will be
when my dad gets back.

406
00:32:11,123 --> 00:32:14,991
"But it's awfully good
talking to a real live hero.

407
00:32:16,662 --> 00:32:18,596
Nim."

408
00:32:18,664 --> 00:32:21,155
W-Wait a minute.
"When my dad gets back"?

409
00:32:23,635 --> 00:32:26,536
Oh, my God.

410
00:32:32,878 --> 00:32:37,042
Who are you, Nim?
How old are you?

411
00:32:38,951 --> 00:32:41,385
Are you all alone,
wherever you are?

412
00:32:58,137 --> 00:33:03,473
<i>What is it?</i>
<i>What does it want out there?</i>

413
00:33:07,713 --> 00:33:10,511
<i>It's coming so fast.</i>

414
00:33:16,889 --> 00:33:21,519
<i>[Gasps]</i>
"Buccaneer?" Buccaneer <i>ship?</i>

415
00:33:22,995 --> 00:33:26,692
<i>"The Oceanographer</i>
<i>and the Great Blue Whale. "

416
00:33:26,765 --> 00:33:28,926
<i>Oh, no.</i>

417
00:33:30,435 --> 00:33:33,097
I think we're being invaded.

418
00:33:47,186 --> 00:33:48,778
[Gasps]

419
00:33:52,925 --> 00:33:55,792
Simply heavenly.
Bloody paradise.

420
00:33:55,861 --> 00:33:58,591
<i>[Man #1]</i>
<i>Not on any map, either.</i>

421
00:33:58,664 --> 00:34:00,791
<i>[First Mate]</i>
<i>Captain, come and take a look at this.</i>

422
00:34:08,373 --> 00:34:12,537
Oh, yes.
This is my bowl of rice, all right.

423
00:34:12,611 --> 00:34:14,545
This'll do quite nicely.
[Chuckles]

424
00:34:14,613 --> 00:34:16,706
- [Groans]
<i>- Look at him.</i>

425
00:34:16,782 --> 00:34:18,374
Pretty little porpoise.

426
00:34:18,450 --> 00:34:22,910
Nature in all its glorious splendor.
[Spits]

427
00:34:25,691 --> 00:34:27,682
Put the barbies over there.

428
00:34:27,759 --> 00:34:30,421
We'll fill the sand
with beach chairs...

429
00:34:30,495 --> 00:34:32,986
and we sell piña coladas
for 10 bucks a pop.

430
00:34:33,065 --> 00:34:34,999
- [Sneezes]
- Shh, Freddie.

431
00:34:35,067 --> 00:34:38,867
<i>You promised everyone a private island,</i>
<i>Captain, and that's exactly what they're getting.</i>

432
00:34:38,937 --> 00:34:43,135
Corporates are gonna love it.
This'll be their own private Buccaneer paradise.

433
00:34:43,208 --> 00:34:46,575
- "Buccaneer paradise"?
<i>- [Captain] Excellent.</i>

434
00:34:46,645 --> 00:34:49,239
<i>We come back in two days.</i>

435
00:34:49,314 --> 00:34:51,441
